@node "Introduction" "Introduction"
@{par}
  @{b}@{u}Introduction@{uu} @{ub}@{par}

Do you use programs that have ugly AppIcons? Do you want to have a program
to have another AppIcon image, but you can't change it?@{par}

Well, here's the final solution for all these problems.@{par}

With NewAppIcon, you can change *every* AppIcon to meet your dreams!@{par}
Replace those awful built-in AppIcons with your preferred ones!@{par}

@endnode
@node "Usage" "Usage"
@{par}
  @{b}@{u}Usage@{uu} @{ub}@{par}

NewAppIcon can only be started from the Shell (preferably from
s:Startup-Sequence right after SetPatch).@{par}

@{lindent 11}@{b}Template:  @{ub}NewAppIcon CONFIG=-c/K,SNOOP=-s/S@{lindent 0}@{par}

You should run NewAppIcon with "@{i}Run >NIL: <NIL:@{ui}".@{par}


@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{par}

@{lindent 9}@{b}CONFIG @{ub}- You can specify a path to your preferred configuration file here.
If you omit this parameter, NewAppIcon will open the file
@{i}ENV:NewAppIcon.cfg@{ui}.@{par}
See the supplied @{"configuration file" link "NewAppIcon.cfg/Main"} for details.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{lindent 9}@{b}SNOOP  @{ub}- This option turns the snoop mode on. Whenever a program wants to
add an AppIcon to the Workbench, you will be prompted with a
requester showing the icon title and the task name. This is useful
if you want to add entries to your configuration file.@{lindent 0}@{par}


You can remove all NewAppIcon patches safely by sending a CTRL+C to its
task.@{par}

NewAppIcon won't eat up *any* CPU time until AppIcons are added or removed
to the Workbench!@{par}

@endnode

